# /hook — Create Custom Hook

## Usage
```
/hook [name] [type]
```

**Types**: `panel` | `compositor` | `data` | `filter`

## Hook Types

### Panel Hook
- Fetches single endpoint via query library
- Exposes data + mutations
- Derived state via service

### Compositor Hook
- Composes 2+ panel hooks
- Aggregates loading/error from all
- Derives statistics and metrics
- Exposes unified refetch

### Data Hook
- Query + mutations in single hook
- Local filter state
- Feedback via toast/notification

### Filter Hook
- Chained queries with conditional `enabled`
- Individual setters for each filter
- Clears dependent filters on parent change

## Phases

### Phase 0 — Reconnaissance
1. Read existing hooks to understand patterns
2. Identify available services and API modules
3. Check existing query keys
{{#if stack}}
4. Read stack patterns in [patterns.md](patterns.md)
{{/if}}

### Phase 1 — Return Type
Create typed return interface with:
- Exposed data (typed)
- State (isLoading, error)
- Actions (refetch, mutate, setters)

### Phase 2 — Implementation
{{#if stack}}
> Stack-specific patterns ({{stack.label}}): see [patterns.md](patterns.md)
{{/if}}
- Query library for server state
- Service for derived logic
- Memoization for reference stability
- Proper side effect cleanup

### Phase 3 — Tests
{{#if stack}}
> Stack-specific test patterns: see [testing.md](testing.md)
{{/if}}
- Mock dependencies (sub-hooks, API, query library)
- Test return shape vs interface
- Test loading/error aggregation
- Test derived logic
- Test mutations and cache invalidation

### Phase 4 — Validation
- Run tests
- Check lint

## Checklist
- [ ] Typed return interface defined
- [ ] Server state via query library
- [ ] Derived logic in service (not in hook)
- [ ] Appropriate memoization (not excessive)
- [ ] Side effect cleanup
- [ ] Tests covering all scenarios
- [ ] Query keys registered
{{/if}}
